segments.text: The way my daddy talks is the main reason that he come over here, because he thought he was running away from wrong.
Because he thinks that people was not legal, they were not doing right things.
And he wants his family to get a chance to live right.
And if anybody made a mistake, well, make it, pay for it, or see that he admitted that he make, don't make somebody else
accuse somebody else or make somebody else pay for the crimes that was committed.
Like those days, he said, we just can't live with that.
We just couldn't.
He said, justice have to be justice no matter what.
And he said, we just couldn't take it anymore.
We just have to stand up around two feet and fight for the rights.
We don't want to know all those things that people were doing.
Just because the man was big man enough to come and

and attack the girls, and the daddy and the mother can't say nothing, just have to stand there and look, or stay there, and don't you go say nothing, because your son will have it, or your husband will.
And you think these things were still happening after 1920?
No, I don't think that no more things will happen, because all those people that were working for that,
They were gone.
They were gone.
They were gone because my daddy said, we saw the trains.
They saw the train that, you see, they sent a locomotive train.
The train was packed with soldiers, horses, and all the equipment.
They can think.
They put on this train.
But they had telephone then.
I don't know what year it was, but they had telephone.
They give some tip off that the train was coming loaded with all those things.
And you know how those mountains are over there?
Well, they sent a locomotive just with no driver.
Just go meet those trains.
And they said those trains, they're still there.
My daddy said, there's no doubt.
They're still there because there's no way nobody can take those.
Because there's what you call a canyon.
And they just fall out.
You can see the crying, the smoke and all that.
And my father-in-law told you that day that he saw little babies crawling like little rats all over.
He said they were
I don't remember, say, about 50 or 100 little babies and little kids that they brought to Sonora and put in an offering.
because their mothers and daddies got killed in the train wreck.
Well, were their mothers and fathers, were their fathers soldiers, or were they refugees?
They were soldiers, too.
And their mothers didn't want to stay there, so they'd take the kids and they'd follow them.
They were soldaderas.
Yeah, they were with them.
And some of them just lived a lot of common law and everything, having kids on top of the train or on the side of the road.
But anyway, all those people, we just have to forget about them.
They're just all gone.
because my daddy said, and the few people that, you know, that didn't get killed, they want to start this other mess.
But, you know, the other people that had more sense, they said, no, we're going to start this.
So most of them flew the country, so they don't report.
And some of them, a lot of kids got killed.
Most of them got killed, because I know, because we were talking about it the other day, that this man got killed when this man's
Like my father-in-law and all of them, they come because, you see, there were a lot of soldiers, you know, still left.
They had good sense.
They said, we're going to put an end to all these people that started this mess.
We're going to put a stop.
And they put a stop.
They did like a caster.
You know, they built a, what you call it, a big hole.
And they just put them over there.
Then he had no gun.
They stabbed him and put him in the hole.
They have to do that because they say, then they get out of there and they spread the, you know, they're going to spread it and make some more people think the way they think.
And they got killed.
They did kill.
Now, the ones that got killed, your father-in-law was with Carranza.
Yes, Carranza.
They was, you know, different generals, I'd say, different generals.
But they were always the same call, attacking the federal government.
They were attacking the federal government
The federal government was crooked as ever because he didn't have no law.
They had no government.
Well, did your father stay with Pablo Gonzalez the whole time, or did he eventually join Villa?
No, he joined Villa because Villa and Gonzalez, they had some partnership.
They were together part of the time.
They were some partners in some way.
I think there's some money.
And they deal with some money and with some ammunition.
Yeah.
I'm trying to remember.
I think Pablo Gonzalez was under Carranza, wasn't he?
And, of course, Carranza and Villa were on the same side for a long time.
And then later were against each other.
Did your father actually meet Villa?
Yeah.
How did he describe him?
Well, he said he, you know how people think about another man.
My daddy used to get up.
He's a little man.
He used to get up.

get up and say oh he said Villa was a man with the knowledge understanding and all that but still and all the things he did he did wrong now that's the way he put it you know when you talk about you know soldier he start telling us so you know think he he was a good man he had a good uh education I think and he had he thought he had a good knowledge but he's dying he died
thinking he was doing right, but he was doing wrong because he come to a place with some girls.
He messed those girls up without any...
He used to be pretty good about that.
Yeah, that's what my daddy said.
So he said, now, you see, you can't put a good man to do those things and then tell the nation that he was a good man.
You can't say that.
He thought he died.
He died.
thinking that he was doing right, but he wasn't doing right.
But what did your father used to say about Pablo Gonzales?
Oh, he thought he was a good man.
He thought he was fighting for the rights of the people.
He thought he was a high standard soldier or man.
What ever happened to Pablo Gonzales?
I've forgotten.
I don't know.
You know, it's been a long time that I haven't talked to him, but he knew everything about those men.
Everything.
They had huerta, and some of them were named huerta.
What did he say about huerta?
Well, you know, they used to send some men to certain places.
They were military men, and they were well-disciplined.
If you don't obey orders, well, he'll come and punch those men.
And they used what you call a sable, like that.
and he'll put somebody to.
And if he say, well, execute that man, and you know, hit him so many legs, and he don't like it, well, you have to hit him again.
And so that teach him a lesson not to disobey the military order.
When they, yes, they send you to somewhere, you better go over there and do whatever we ever say, or else don't come back.
You know, that he believes in not a military discipline, because he was a soldier.
He knew his work and everything.
Now what rank did you say you thought he had?
Well, he thought he was, my daddy thought he was fighting for the right of the... Oh, what rank?
Oh, rank.
He was a captain.
He was a captain in the army of Pablo Gonzales.
Pablo Gonzales, yeah.
He was a captain.
And you know, my brother used to laugh because he's a little bitter man.
He said, oh, this man, he don't know nothing.
And you know, my daddy...
Every time he tells us something, he says, and that's an order.
And that's an order.
And my mother said, he's not talking to you as a father.
He's talking to you as a soldier.
I was giving you some orders.
And you know, when he was going to whip us, he said, y'all look for the belt.
And we just looking for the belt.
He had one, but he wanted us to go and get the thing for you one to be executed.
And after we don't find the belt, but he got his.
And he just give about two or three licks, but he'll tell you why and where and when.
And yeah, he was not kind of a man, he'd go bang, bang.
No, he'll explain to you.
I told you not to do this.
Yes.
Why did you do it?
Well, something went wrong.
Well, this is to remember not to do it again.
And boy,
Every time Mother said, well, I won't tell you, Daddy.
We were, Mother, don't tell him.
We know he was going to get it.
But he said that he thought Villa was, in the sense of a soldier, he was a good soldier, what you call a good soldier.
He had a good understanding, good knowledge.
He said, but he was wrong.
He was doing wrong.
He got to meet him in person, talk with him, eat with him, and everything.
Did your father ever talk about any battles he was in or anything?
Yes, he said he talks about some of them.
And then he talked about sometimes they were so thirsty, they were so hungry.
He said, well, sometimes we have to shoot our own horse and eat it because there was nothing else to eat.
Yeah, he used to talk about, he said he don't believe in

the word is seen in any good in any language because he said he saw a lot of things that he didn't have to see if they didn't even you know think about doing things right he said but uh i saw some things that boy it just he just don't want to think about now that he got an old little man he said but it was some some tough days that we didn't have nothing to eat and then especially when you start shooting he said you thought we'd get so dry
And he said, look like you, and you don't know, and you can see just the fire.
And now you can see the fire just like a firecracker.
And you're just shooting at nobody because you're shooting just, you don't know if that bullet is going to hit you or nothing.
It's just a chance that you're going to take.
He said sometimes they shoot all night.
And see, the next morning, there'll be some children, but that much children.
They shouldn't all die.
I don't know how many around.
Well, now, so many years after the revolution, what kind of place do you think Mexico is to live?
Well, Mexico is, the way I went over there, the way it looks, it's all right.
I think Mexico is doing all right.
Because I went to all these places that I wanted to go.
Where all did you go?
I went to all the department stores.
I went to the stores.
I went to the church.
In what town?
In Monclova.
In Monclova.
And they got everything that we got.
They got everything that we got.
They haven't missed anything.
One thing, just one thing that I saw, that they should have so many babies.
So many, you know, the families are, the couples are real babies.

loaded with babies you know a couple about around 20 25 years old or they they already got by six or seven babies you know and they're so young they look so pretty and the babies are real pretty but i think that's where they're i won't say a mistake but i think that's what they need to do some little work you know if they had a they'd have a more

protection or something like that that we they don't have to deal with so many little babies and that you know sometimes a lot of babies are not are not good for the girl for the for the female and sometimes i don't know i'm not against the babies but what it is that they they haven't got any any well the neighborhood that i went they got no no sinks no no tubs like we do no no no nothing like uh

the restrooms is outside and all that, and that maybe in the future they're going to, there's some communities that they already got everything, but now these other ones, they are just about building.
They just got a little room like this, and a whole eight, nine, or two little kids live there, and the mom and the dad, and the kitchen and everything is the same.
Who were you visiting when you were there?
I visited my mom.
My son lost his mom and dad.
Your son lost his mother and dad?
Yeah.
And he's from Montclova?
Yeah, he's from Montclova.
But you see, well, they well off because they got a big brick house bigger than mine.
And it's brand new.
They just made it.
Now they well off.
They want the vices.
But what I'm talking about, you know, the other little... You went out to some other parts of town.
Some other parts of town.
And the streets are not very...
They're not fixed, you know.
They just got dirt roads and just a lot of rocks and everything and just a bunch of little kids in the streets and all that.
But it's the same way as here.
But what it is, they all go to school.
That's one thing I've got to say.
That little boy, little girl, about six, seven years, he know how to read and write in Spanish just like the little kids over here in English.
And they know how to multiply and everything.
You know, that's what I admired in.
But I still say that, like I told my son-in-law, he says that, yeah, I just got two, Mom, and I've been married about six years, seven years.
He said, but that's when they got on one, Mom, who liked to have so many babies.
He said, well, because I noticed they don't have any.
Mm-hmm.
Who is your son-in-law?
What religion are you?
You're Methodist, aren't you?
Well, my son-in-law was Catholic, but until he come and meet my girl over here, he become a Methodist.
He joined the Methodist church?
He joined the Methodist church, and he said he liked it.
And then he said he didn't like to deal with so many babies because he said it's hard for the men to support them, baby.
He said that he just don't know how these people support those babies.
We saw so many, you know, we went close to Christmas, and they were all out there chopping.
I don't know how many little babies.
They were about this big, about this big.
There's like a little letter and another one and another one away from me.
I tell my husband, they look pretty, all right.
I said, but I hate to be here with you two.
He said, because I just wondered how they do to support all those babies.
And then my husband said, well, how did you do with yours?
I said, yeah, but it was not so mean.
I don't know, maybe they got more tap than we do to support all those ladies.
And they sleep on the floor, just in the little rug or something.
And they got no heaters.
I didn't see no heaters over there.
I saw a stove, you know, running with a butane.
Everybody got butane over there.
They believe a lot in butane.
Even in the country, they got butane.
But I didn't see no heaters.
Very few.
There are very few houses heated in Mexico.
It used to be that way here when we moved to Texas in 1950.
Nobody had heat.
And we were worse.
I guess you didn't have heat when you were growing up in the Brazos Valley.
Well, we had a chimney.
You had a fireplace?
A fireplace, yeah.
That's what I was talking about.
I said, you know, we'll be here.
It's a lot of different, because we have some wood.
We have some wood for fireplace.
We have some wood.
But I didn't see no heaters, no kind in the house.
But of course, it's not so cold over there, neither.
No, not as often, anyway.
That's what I was thinking about.
It's not too cold, neither, because it's just more of the south than we do here.
But that's why I think that those people got everything.
Everything.
I went to look for a stanchion like that, and it was there.
And the bub and everything, they showed me everything.
And they got everything.
Paints.
I was looking for some paint, and they showed me the paint and the brush and everything.
They got everything.
Everything.
Do you feel like they have problems now with the law and all the kinds of things that used to happen?
No, no, I don't think so because those people are more, you know, more aware of the thing because they know that if anybody do something, they get what they coming.
They don't have to pay for the crime they commit.
You feel like they solve those problems.
Yeah, those problems, yeah.
And then this truck had a lot of means that they were in penitentiary.
And you know, all the men we got here in Huntsville in the penitentiary, well, we didn't have to pay the city nothing.
We bring all those men to clean the city.
Over there, they brought all the men from penitentiary to clean the city.
And the guards was there.
They was cleaning all the city.
And told my son-in-law, my husband told my son-in-law, one of those men said they from penitentiary.
They were different.
with the struts.
They were in penitentiary.
He said, but we don't have to pay no city people.
They don't know, we ain't got no city people.
Those are the people that come and do the cleaning.
Well, it's kind of the same way in Huntsville.
The prison guards, I mean, the prisoners in Huntsville do a lot of the work on the college campus and the parks and everything.
They do all that over there, too.
Well, you see, what I mean is not that, you know, we don't take them out of there to come and clean the brine.
No, not the brine.
That's what I meant.
But they do use them in Huntsville.
Yeah, they do their own cultivation.
They grow their own food.
That's what I heard.
I see them working on the field.
But what I meant is that the prisoners don't have to come and clean.
Clean brine.
Clean brine.
They come from over there to the city, to the streets and get the garbage.
But they do over there.
That way the government is having a little help there.
Is there a big prison in Monclova?
No, I didn't ask Johnny, but they saw those men and they just said that they were people to see.
I hope not, but my boy and a bunch of boys went to Monterey.
They went to the orphan.
They said they had so many little boys, but from
eight, nine, and ten.
Almost the same age.

And they went to the convent to sing for the nuns because the Methodist from Dallas, they furnished the bus and they gave him $700 just to make a trip, you know, to let the, what you call the Southwest Comforts to get involved in Mexico to see what they can work over there, develop something or see something or something.
And they went over there, and they were very impressed, and they would approach my boy and say, Mama, you can see all the little boys.
They ain't got no mommy nor daddy.
They were little boys.
But my boys' organization, they're going to give $75 each year, which is almost $1,000 over there, so the little orphan kids can have at least a good meal every now and then.
Did he find out why there were so many orphans?
No, they didn't talk about that.
They just said that there were orphans.
The orphans, they took them over there.
The ministers took them over there to sing and to learn them to say things in English.
And they sing in English and Spanish.
So they can get something different from what they've been teaching over there.
They like it.
The little boys like it.
And then they went to the convent.
They went to the plaza.
They went to all the places, you know.
They stayed about a week or so, but my boy said they were very impressive.
He said the town was good, and the names were good, and the people were so polite, and they liked it.
Yeah, I like Monterey.
It's a nice city.
Yeah, I like the food.
I do like the food very much.
And I told my husband, I said, I think they got me.
The way they talk, I said, they got law and order.
I said, ain't nothing wrong.
They're just a lot of people, that's all.
There's a lot of Spanish people, that's all.
In Monclova, 78,000.
That's a pretty good size.
Yeah, the population is 78,000.
You can see miles and miles, and you can see corners and streets and pools.
People, I just see one colored boy.
And he talk in Spanish.
I don't know what he say.
He was sitting at the window, and another boy approached him and said the shoes that were there, he liked that.
But he said it in Spanish, so I don't know where he comes from.
But I didn't say no one Anglo or nothing else, but just Spanish.
And I thought, when I saw that color board, I said, where did he come from?
And he showed some shoe that he was a bison shoe.
It cost about 200 pesos.
Now your husband's family came from Mexico in 1918.
Was your husband born here or there?
There.
He was born there.
He was born in June 1917.
And he doesn't really remember coming up here.
No, he was nine months old.
And I was less than a year.
Me too.
I don't remember nothing about that.
But now I remember that I took that trip.
I remember everything good and I'll never forget.
Have you been just the one time?
One time.
How long ago was that?
Last year.
Last year?
Last year, but I went to Laredo first.
I went to Laredo, but I've been taken to Crip.
And this year I did want to take one, but it was a time for my vacation, so I couldn't take it.
And so they went over there, but I'm planning to take them home to Oklahoma.
Yeah, to see your parents.
Yeah.
And your father.
My dad, yeah.
I want to see.
How did you happen to meet your husband?
We was living here at the bottom, what you call the breast of that, the other bottom.
And we moved to Hillock because this boy was going to marry my sister.
And then he said that they have some good houses and good
Then maybe my daddy can make better trade over there than over here.
My daddy, well, let's go over there.
And so my sister got married, and she had a big wedding.
And my husband and his brother happened to come to the wedding.
And that's where they, he saw me.
I saw him, and he saw me.
And then about a year later, he wrote me a letter as I was staying in the state of Oklahoma.
We were working over there, and I received a letter from him that he wants to have some love affair or something with me.
And so I didn't really think, thought about who he was.
I said, well, we have a bunch of girls over there, and all the girls had letters and everything.
And they said, well, let's sit over here and make a decision.
What should I say?
Well, let's say yes just for the fun of it.
And he didn't even know who he is.
And so I did wrote the letter back, answered the letter back.
When I come back from the state of Oklahoma, that I come back to him, he show up.
And he said that he was the one that wrote me a letter.
And so from there, we started from there.
After a year, and three months, and three weeks, and a hundred days, we got back.
Did your parents let you actually go out on dates?
No.
No, they didn't believe in that.
No, they don't want the boys to come see the girls.
They don't want the boys to get the girls out of the house.
We couldn't get out of the house.
We had a little well about a block or two from the house.
We just have to go get the water from the faucet in the back.
We traveled back and forth, of course, to get some water and water all day.
But that's all we could do.
And you made it the well.
No, the boys, they used to have a baseball diamond over there.
And all the boys and men from the farm get together over there to play.
We just go over there and get the water and look.
Just about five minutes and you better come back because you can't stay there.
No, they were very strict at that point.
We couldn't, we couldn't go out.
Well, actually, I never did go out with a boy myself one day or one evening or one night, one hour or so.
I used to talk to my husband about twice.
It was in my sister-in-law's house.
He made a visit over there.
This other girl happened to take me over there to work playing the record.
And he was there.
And he said, well, finally I saw Maggie along.
And he talk about, you know, he was older than me.
We were talking about plants and wedding plants and all that.
And I began to get scared.
How old were you then?
I was about 16.
I was just shaking.
I said, no, no, no, no.
He said, yes, he said.
Go and ask your father, you better not come over the house if you don't want my father to raise him some cane.
He said, well, then I'll wait.
How much will you want me to wait now?
I don't know.
And he keep, you know, boys, would be boys, he keep, you know, he was 22.
Well, he was 21 then, and he was 22, and then he was 23.
And when Geek got married, he was 24.
He was still waiting all this time.
So when you got married, you were how old?
17, yeah.
And, well, did he finally come see your father?
No, he never did come.
He was scared.
You know, the boys used to have a lot of respect for that.
Well, how did you happen to get married?
We just eloped.
You eloped.
Oh.
And just run away.
Yeah, just run away.
He come to my house and

at night after a thief and just took me to his house and then we were the next day the next day they they called the minister and you know he always been a methodist he called the minister and said well you have to forgive me i need a wife and i think i'll look for one and i found it and this is the girl no one married and the minister said well there's nothing wrong we'll get you license and and we'll be here tonight to marry you
Was it all right with his parents?
They were in on it.
They were all right because his son had committed a crime there because he had no business going to that house and bringing a girl.
But then I was under age, you know, 17.
But he said, well, as long as she don't complain, we're not going to say anything.
My daddy didn't complain then because he was mad.
He said he didn't want to take any part in the wedding when my husband
bought me to town, bought me my dress and my everything and the wedding cake and everything and we just, we were married that night.
Did your mother and daddy come?
No, they didn't come.
How long was it before they came around?
Five years.
Five years?
Five years before they got over?
They got over.
Five years I had to stay away from the house because they didn't want
Because they were Catholics.
And they think that the Protestants and the Catholics should get involved because they thought it was a sin.
Well, we didn't see it that way.
We love each other, and we need each other, and we do care about no religion.
Well, how about your sisters, though?
Did they have trouble, too, when they got married?
No, my sister was married to a Catholic man.
I see.
So one of the reasons that your father didn't accept your husband was the religion.
Yeah, but my sister had a pretty wedding.
That's where I got to meet him.
My husband was this man of...
friends and they invited him to the wedding.
We set the table and I remember that I had a dress that my mother had made me.
It was a blue, a blue taffeta dress.
A lot of, you know, shiny, real shiny.
I thought I was the queen because I never did wear one like that.
And I was so impressed by that dress and I thought I was going crazy.
And then she put some white
a collar and a little, like a little, she made like a little tie.
And I would just, you know, go in places and then he asked the question, who is she?
I said, that's the bride's sister.
Oh, well, very interesting.
Any more sisters around here?
She said, no, she's the only one.
Well, we'll get it before the
Thank you so much.
I was just thinking, for a long time, a lot of parents were pretty strict with their daughters.
What about now?
Is it that way now?
Well, some Spanish men still, but some don't.
They already find out that, you know, like me and my husband said this way when we got married, if we ever get having any family,
We're not going to be a sire because they were hard on us.
We enjoy the life.
We're just working and not enjoying.
We can go to the dance.
We can go to the movie.
We can go to church.
We can go nothing.
Nowhere.
You stay there like an old maid at the age of 16 or 17.
And my husband said, yes, we're never going to be with the girls.
Now my oldest daughter got married at 22.
And we didn't have no problem.
And she didn't go out.
She didn't go out.
I've got one over there.
She's 21, and she don't go out.
And we didn't tell her not to go out.
I tell my husband, well, I don't know what happened.
I said, I got my other girl.
She's 15.
She don't go out with boys.
And she's 21.
And I said, I haven't seen a boy, you know, framed and running around or asking for a date or nothing.
And she said, I don't know.
I tell my husband, how about us?
We were just tied to a tree.
And I said, I didn't tie my girls.
I said, well, y'all go and see the world and make your own decisions and work and have a good time, have a lot of fun with people.
My kids are going to church.
They go to the meetings, to the church, to the service, to sing here and there and over there and anywhere.
It's not one thing.
That one, Joseph, she went to that racetrack yesterday and walked 20 miles.
Yes, bless her heart.
She was limping.
Yes, she's got burns all over here.
Is she the one that's 21?
Mm-hmm.
She's 21, I said, and I tell my husband, I say, and she's having a lot of fun.
That car is hers, and she worked, and she paid her car.
And where is she working now?
Coca-Cola.
At the Coca-Cola, yeah.
Before that, she worked somewhere.
with me over there when she was in high school.
She was about 14.
She always thought about buying a car.
She bought that car and she's paying for it.
